Tell HN: Do not store any funds in PayPal or use them for anything critical
text:
I know this has been covered over and over, but I always thought there must be more to the story when someones account was permanently banned. Well, it happened to me, one of the most plain and boring consumer users of PayPal ever.

I have used PayPal for over a decade, usually once or twice a month to make small purchases when buying something off Craigslist or Facebook marketplace. I also occasionally use it to split dinner with friends. I don't use it for business and I don't use it for anything sketchy.

I recently received an email from PayPal saying that my account had been permanently banned. No appeal, no reason given. I logged in separately to make sure this was a real email, at first I thought it must be phishing. It was real.

The only thing I can think of which might have precipitated this. I got a few invoice requests though PayPal a while ago from people/businesses I had never heard of. This is a well known and documented scam where they spam invoices en-masse and hope some people pay them accidentally (I did not pay them, but the PayPal UI makes this very easy to do and there is no way to decline or dismiss the requests).

Not a big deal for me since I don't use PayPal for anything critical, but I figured a reminder was in order in case anyone still thinks it won't happen to them. If it could happen to me, it can happen to anyone.

Ask HN: Best tactics for product feedback and when is enough enough?
text:
Hey everyone, we all know how important it is to gather feedback on our projects and ideas. But how do you go about doing it? And how do you know when you've gathered enough feedback to move forward with your plans?

I'd love to hear about your strategies for gathering feedback, whether you use online surveys, focus groups, or other research methods. Do you rely on personal connections and informal conversations, or do you seek out more structured feedback sessions? And how many people do you typically need to engage with before you feel confident in the feedback you're receiving?

As a reference, YC partners have written some popular blog posts on the topic of customer feedback, such as "How to Get Startup Ideas" by Paul Graham and "How to Talk to Users" by Adora Cheung. Have you found these posts helpful in your own feedback-gathering process?

Ask HN: What projects to build as a first time programmer?
text:
We often hear that university courses and books can't make us programmers. It is our own grit and perseverance that helps us develop that skill.

Often the suggestion is to start building things in the language of your choice (e.g Python) after learning the basic constructs of programming like built in data types, functions, iteration, etc.

But what things to build if you habe no idea what can be built using computer programs.

Is there a set of projects that someone can start with and then discover their calling as to which domain they want to build projects in.

Ask HN: Free Email Hosting for Nonprofits?
text:
Hack Club is a nonprofit network of hackathons, student-led coding clubs, and open source projects. Our website is https://hackclub.com and our GitHub is https://github.com/hackclub.

We have been receiving free email hosting from Google Workspace and providing it to the Hack Club network, but we recently hit the domain limit (600 domains) on Google Workspace for Nonprofits. Each domain is typically a hackathon or a chapter at a high school.

Does anyone have any recommendations for email hosts that we could look into? As a mostly volunteer-driven nonprofit, we can't afford pay per-user pricing as there are thousands and thousands of accounts.
